Motivation is fleeting, you need discipline.

Write every day.
>bullshit at work is still pissing me off
write about that
>family problems are making it difficult to focus
write about that
>i just feel tired and sad all the time
write about that
>i don't like what i wrote yesterday and it's bad
then write about why it's bad

Exorcise your goddamn demons onto a piece of paper for as long as it takes to get them out of the way. Writing organizes your thoughts and helps to put them in a place other than your head. The only way through your shitty motivation is to make the motivation a non-factor in how much and how often you write.

A lot, but the most important part of drawing doesn't happen on the paper but between your ears. It's all very difficult and long-winded to explain, but you need to keep in mind that a drawing is the representation of a 3D shape on a 2D plane.
It all sounds very hocus-pocus until you start to feel a glimpse of being able to do it.
It's difficult to learn by yourself and there is only so much I can explain on the fly, but seek far and wide for resources. Everyone has to find their own way in the end, but you will need help to get that far. Good luck.
